<section class="hero">
  <h1>Take back<br />your group chat.</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Eleven works just like the messengers you're used to — groups, photos,
    reactions, replies — without the ads, the tracking, or the big-tech
    company in the middle. Your conversations stay between you and the people
    you invited.
  </p>
  <div class="cta">
    <a class="btn btn-primary" href="#get">Get Eleven</a>
    <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/security/">How it stays private</a>
  </div>
  <p class="fine">
    Invite-only — there's no public sign-up. Someone already in a chat sends you
    a link.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="pains" aria-label="Why Eleven exists">
  <h2>Ever wondered&hellip;</h2>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why is chatting to your friends run by big tech?</h3>
    <p>
      A group chat doesn't need a social network attached, an algorithm choosing
      what you see, or a business model built on knowing who you talk to.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why do you need a mobile number to talk to people you already know?</h3>
    <p>
      Your phone number is an identity you hand over before you've said a word.
      Eleven has no accounts at all — you join with a secret link from someone
      already inside.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why choose between owning your chat and actually enjoying it?</h3>
    <p>
      Self-hosting usually means wrestling servers and losing the polish.
      Eleven is one small server you can run yourself — with an app that feels
      like the ones everyone already knows.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="features" aria-label="What makes Eleven different">
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>Feels like home</h3>
    <p>
      Groups and DMs, photos, reactions, replies, link previews, push
      notifications. Everything you expect from a modern messenger — nothing to
      relearn.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>No logins, no passwords</h3>
    <p>
      No phone number, no email, nothing to sign up for. You join with a
      one-time secret link — nothing to remember, nothing to phish, nothing to
      leak.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>Yours to run</h3>
    <p>
      Each chat is its own tiny private server — easy to set up for your
      friends, your family, your kids. You decide who's in, and no one else
      gets a say.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>Private by design</h3>
    <p>
      Messages are end-to-end encrypted, so not even the server can read them.
      <a href="/security/">See how the security model works&nbsp;&rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="pains" aria-label="Eleven and AI">
  <h2>Where AI fits</h2>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Built and audited by the best models there are</h3>
    <p>
      Eleven is built with the latest AI models and security-audited by them
      too — including a security review by Claude&nbsp;Fable. The source is
      available while we're in beta, so you don't have to take our word (or
      the AI's) for any of it: the code is there to check.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>In your chats only if you invite it</h3>
    <p>
      You choose how much AI to bring to your own server — an assistant in one
      group, a single quiet bot, or none at all. Nothing is switched on for
      you. Bring as little as you want, including nothing.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

